    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Three Reportable Segments and Their Disclosed Interdependencies\n\n## The Three Segments\n\n| Segment | Description (as disclosed) |\n|---|---|\n| **Space** | Designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets (Falcon, Dragon, Starship in development) to provide high-cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space at unprecedented scale. |\n| **Connectivity** | Operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband and communications network powered by over 9,600 Starlink satellites in LEO, delivering connectivity to millions of consumer, enterprise, and government customers across 164 markets, including Starlink Mobile (satellite-to-mobile texting and voice). |\n| **AI** | Operates a vertically integrated AI platform spanning the Grok frontier LLM, AI solutions for consumer and enterprise customers, X (a real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform), and AI computational infrastructure. |\n\n---\n\n## Disclosed Interdependencies and Cross-Segment Relationships\n\n### 1. Space as the Foundational Enabler of All Other Segments\n\nThe most explicit interdependency statement in the document is:\n\n> "While our **Space segment provides us with a foundational competitive advantage that enables all other parts of our business**, our Connectivity and AI segments are expected to be the primary driver of revenue growth in the near term."\n\nThis establishes a unidirectional dependency: Space underpins Connectivity and AI, but the near-term revenue growth is expected to come from the latter two.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Starship as a Cross-Segment Enabler (Space → Connectivity and AI)\n\nStarship is described not merely as a Space-segment product but as infrastructure serving all three segments:\n\n> "Starship, a fully reusable transportation system that is designed to carry **crew, cargo, satellites, and data centers** to Earth orbit, the Moon, Mars, and beyond."\n\n- **Satellites** → Connectivity segment (Starlink constellation deployment and refresh)\n- **Data centers** → AI segment (in-orbit AI compute infrastructure)\n\nThe risk factors make this linkage explicit and bidirectional in terms of operational risk:\n\n> "Unexpected design modifications, supply chain disruptions, anomalies, environmental issues, and other unforeseen technical challenges could result in delays or failures to deploy Starship on our anticipated schedule, which would delay or impede our ability to achieve our **other business objectives, such as the deployment of our next-generation satellites [Connectivity], the expansion of our satellite-to-mobile connectivity services [Connectivity], and deployment of in-orbit AI compute infrastructure [AI]**."\n\nThis is the single most detailed disclosure of cross-segment operational dependency: a failure or delay in the Space segment\'s Starship program directly impairs the Connectivity segment\'s satellite deployment and mobile services expansion, and the AI segment\'s orbital compute infrastructure deployment.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Terafab (Space Manufacturing) → AI Infrastructure Scaling\n\nThe Terafab manufacturing facility, a Space-segment capability, is explicitly linked to the AI segment\'s competitive position:\n\n> "We expect significant speed and cost advantages from Terafab\'s vertical integration. We believe this will provide us with a **critical competitive advantage in the race to scale AI infrastructure, especially as we begin our orbital AI compute satellite deployments**."\n\nThis discloses that Space-segment manufacturing infrastructure is being leveraged to serve AI-segment strategic objectives, specifically orbital AI compute.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Vertically Integrated Innovation Engine (Shared Operational Framework)\n\nThe company frames all three segments as components of a single integrated system rather than independent businesses:\n\n> "We have created what we believe to be the world\'s most ambitious **vertically integrated innovation engine** that captures significant growth across three domains: Space, Connectivity, and AI."\n\nThis is reinforced by the operational principles statement:\n\n> "We continuously reduce unit costs while increasing **launch cadence [Space], satellite network [Connectivity], and AI hosting capacity [AI]**."\n\nAll three are described as being optimized together under a shared operational discipline, suggesting shared infrastructure and processes (though no specific cost allocations are disclosed).\n\n---\n\n### 5. Shared Talent Pool and Employee Ownership\n\nWhile the segments are financially distinct, the workforce is described as a shared resource:\n\n> "Our engineering-oriented organization maintains access to some of the world\'s most selective talent pool. In 2025, we accepted under 2% of our engineering applicants."\n\n> "Our broad-based employee ownership program ensures that those who help us build the future are also direct beneficiaries of our success."\n\n> "Average tenure across our broader SpaceX leadership team of 12 years."\n\nThere is no disclosure of headcount allocated by segment or intersegment employee charges. The talent pool and equity program are described at the enterprise level, not the segment level.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Shared Technology: Reusability, Automation, and Vertical Integration\n\nSeveral technology themes are described as cross-cutting:\n\n- **Full and rapid reusability** (Space launch vehicles) is described as enabling lower-cost deployment of satellites (Connectivity) and data centers (AI).\n- **High-volume satellite manufacturing** and rapid constellation refresh cycles (Connectivity) are listed alongside reusable launch as parallel industry trends the company is capitalizing on.\n- **AI, automation, and robotics** are described as accelerating engineering iteration cycles and streamlining operations across the company — implying AI-segment capabilities feed back into Space and Connectivity operations.\n\nThe core competitive strengths list includes "Extreme vertical integration enabling high velocity and superior cost efficiency at scale" as an enterprise-level strength, not a segment-specific one.\n\n---\n\n### 7. What Is NOT Disclosed\n\nSeveral items that one might expect in a segment interdependency disclosure are **absent** from the provided text:\n\n| Item | Disclosure Status |\n|---|---|\n| Intersegment revenue / transfer pricing | **Not disclosed.** The segment financial tables show no "intersegment" or "eliminations" line. Revenue appears to be external only. |\n| Shared infrastructure cost allocations | **Not disclosed.** No methodology for allocating shared property, plant, and equipment or overhead across segments is described. |\n| Shared employee headcount by segment | **Not disclosed.** Talent is described at the enterprise level only. |\n| Intersegment technology licensing | **Not disclosed.** No mention of one segment licensing technology to another. |\n| CODM cross-segment resource transfer mechanics | **Partially disclosed.** The CODM "organizes the Company, manages resource allocations, and measures performance among three operating and reportable segments" based on segment income (loss) from operations. The text cuts off after "The Company\'s CODM does not evaluate operating and reportable segments using…" — the remainder is not in the provided chunks. |\n| Segment-level asset allocation | **Not disclosed** (the sentence referenced above is truncated). |\n\n---\n\n### 8. Financial Scale of the Interdependencies (Q1 2026)\n\nThe segment financials illustrate the asymmetry of the interdependency model:\n\n| Metric (Q1 2026, $M) | Space | Connectivity | AI | Total |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Revenue | 619 | 3,257 | 818 | 4,694 |\n| R&D expense | 930 | 205 | 2,379 | 3,514 |\n| Capital expenditures | 1,052 | 1,332 | 7,723 | 10,107 |\n| Income (loss) from operations | (662) | 1,188 | (2,469) | (1,943) |\n\nThe Space segment is loss-making but absorbing $930M in R&D for Starship — the vehicle that enables the other two segments. The AI segment is the largest consumer of capital ($7.7B in capex) and R&D ($2.4B), much of which appears to depend on Space-segment launch and manufacturing capabilities for its orbital compute strategy. Connectivity is the only profitable segment and is described as the primary near-term revenue growth driver.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe disclosed interdependency model is essentially **hub-and-spoke with Space at the center**: the Space segment\'s launch vehicles (particularly Starship) and manufacturing infrastructure (Terafab) are explicitly described as enabling the Connectivity segment\'s satellite deployment and the AI segment\'s orbital compute infrastructure. The company frames itself as a single "vertically integrated innovation engine" with shared talent, shared operational philosophy, and shared technology themes (reusability, automation, vertical integration). However, the financial segment reporting treats the segments as operationally distinct — no intersegment revenue, cost allocations, or transfer pricing mechanisms are disclosed in the provided text, and the CODM evaluates each segment on a standalone segment-income basis.',
