    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial disclosures, here is a detailed description of the company’s segment reporting structure, definitions, and the allocation of revenue and costs following the post-merger realignment.\n\n### Post-Merger Realignment and Segment Reporting Structure\nFollowing the Mergers, the Company evaluated how to view and measure the performance of the combined entity and determined that a realignment of the historical segment structures was necessary. Effective Q1 2026, the Company’s Chief Executive Officer, acting as the Chief Operating Decision Maker (“CODM”), reorganized the Company into three operating and reportable segments: **(i) Space, (ii) Connectivity, and (iii) AI**. Prior period segment presentations have been conformed to this new reporting structure.\n\n### CODM Resource Allocation and Performance Measurement\nThe CODM assesses performance and allocates resources to the operating segments based on **segment income (loss) from operations**. The CODM evaluates this metric by comparing actual income (loss) from operations to historical results and previously forecasted financial information. The disclosures note that the CODM does not evaluate operating and reportable segments using consolidated net income or other corporate-level metrics below the operating line (such as interest expense, interest income, or other income/expense). \n\n### Segment Definitions\nThe Company defines its three vertically integrated segments as follows:\n*   **Space:** Designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets (such as Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, and the in-development Starship) to provide high-cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space at unprecedented scale.\n*   **Connectivity:** Operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband data and communications network powered by thousands of Starlink satellites in Low-Earth Orbit, delivering connectivity to millions of consumer, enterprise, and government customers across 164 countries.\n*   **AI:** Operates a vertically integrated AI platform spanning a frontier Large Language Model (Grok), AI solutions for consumer and enterprise customers, X (a real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform), and AI computational infrastructure.\n\n### Revenue and Cost Allocation\nRevenue and costs are allocated directly to the segments based on the activities that drive them. Below is a breakdown of how these are recognized and allocated across the segments:\n\n**1. Space Segment**\n*   **Revenue:** Generated solely from external customer launches and customer activities. It is divided into:\n    *   *Launch Services:* Fixed-price contracts (1 to 5 years) recognized at a point in time upon the launch or deployment of the customer’s payload.\n    *   *Launch & Development:* Fixed-price contracts (1 to 14 years) for government space programs recognized over time using the cost-to-cost input method.\n*   **Costs:** Cost of revenue reflects the costs of customer launches. Research and development (R&D) heavily reflects investments in the next-generation Starship vehicle. Selling, general, and administrative (SG&A) expenses include allocated employee compensation costs (salaries, benefits, share-based compensation) for sales, facilities, legal, finance, IT, HR, and other administrative staff, as well as depreciation and corporate aircraft costs. \n\n**2. Connectivity Segment**\n*   **Revenue:** Generated from (i) broadband and mobile connectivity services provided through Starlink (recognized over time as services are consumed) and (ii) the sale of Starlink Kits (terminals). All of the company\'s "products" revenue is attributable to this segment.\n*   **Costs:** Cost of revenue includes the manufacturing costs of Starlink Kits and significant depreciation expenses related to the satellites placed into orbit. \n\n**3. AI Segment**\n*   **Revenue:** Generated from Advertising (on the X platform) and AI Solutions & Infrastructure (Grok subscriptions and compute infrastructure services). \n*   **Costs:** R&D is the largest expense driver, heavily impacted by the depreciation of GPU hardware, cloud computing costs, and data center infrastructure expenses due to AI data center expansions. \n\n### Shared Resources, Transfer Pricing, and Intersegment Arrangements\nA critical aspect of the Company\'s segment reporting is the treatment of shared launch capacity between the Space segment and the Connectivity/AI segments:\n\n*   **Intersegment Launch Capacity:** The Space segment provides launch services to deploy Starlink satellites for the Connectivity segment. The Company **does not recognize any inter-segment revenue** for these internal launches. \n*   **Capitalization of Internal Launch Costs:** Instead of recording a transfer price or intersegment revenue, the costs associated with launching Starlink satellites are capitalized directly within the Connectivity segment as part of "satellites" in Property, plant, and equipment, net, and depreciated over time.\n*   **Future Allocations:** The Company currently allocates a significant amount of its launch capacity to the Connectivity segment and expects to allocate a significant amount of launch capacity to the AI segment in the future (e.g., for deploying data centers to Earth orbit, the Moon, or Mars).\n*   **Strategic Impact on Segment Financials:** Because the Space segment\'s revenue only reflects external customer launches—and not the massive internal demand from the Connectivity and AI segments—its revenue scale and growth are relatively lower compared to the rest of the company. The segment financials do not reflect the foundational strategic value and shared resources the Space segment provides to bolster the growth of the Connectivity and AI segments.',
        error=None,
