    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Relationship Between the AI Segment (Grok/X) and the Connectivity Segment (Starlink)\n\nBased on the provided text, the document **does not disclose any specific data flows, content distribution arrangements, or shared infrastructure** between X/Grok (AI segment) and Starlink (Connectivity segment). The two segments are described as distinct operating units with separate functions, revenue streams, and infrastructure.\n\n## What the Document Does Disclose\n\n### 1. Segments Are Operationally Distinct\nThe AI segment and Connectivity segment are presented as separate reportable segments with independent descriptions:\n\n- **Connectivity**: Operates a "worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband network powered by thousands of Starlink satellites in Low-Earth Orbit, delivering connectivity to millions of consumer, enterprise, and government customers."\n- **AI**: Operates "a vertically integrated AI platform spanning a frontier LLM Grok, AI solutions for consumer and enterprise customers, X — a real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform — and AI computational infrastructure."\n\nNo inter-segment revenue, cost allocations, or shared service arrangements between AI and Connectivity are disclosed.\n\n### 2. The Space Segment Is the Shared Dependency — Not AI↔Connectivity Directly\nThe only explicitly disclosed cross-segment operational linkage involving both segments runs **through the Space segment**, not directly between AI and Connectivity:\n\n> "We allocate a significant amount of launch capacity to our Connectivity segment, and expect to allocate a significant amount to our AI segment in the future."\n\nThis means the Space segment launches Starlink satellites for Connectivity (with costs capitalized within Connectivity rather than recognized as Space segment revenue), and may launch AI-related payloads in the future. This is a Space-to-other-segments relationship, not an AI-to-Connectivity relationship.\n\n### 3. X\'s Data Role Is Internal to the AI Segment\nThe document describes X as a data and distribution engine, but only **within the AI segment itself** (i.e., feeding Grok), not as a service to Starlink:\n\n> "X — our real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform — and AI computational infrastructure."\n\n> "Our access to real-time data on X creates a significant strategic advantage."\n\n> "\'X\' refers to our real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform that serves as a foundational distribution and data engine for the AI ecosystem."\n\nThis describes X-to-Grok data flows, not X-to-Starlink or Starlink-to-Grok flows.\n\n### 4. Aspirational Vision of AI in Space — No Current Operational Link\nThe document contains forward-looking, aspirational language about AI infrastructure in space, but frames this as a future vision rather than a current or disclosed operational arrangement:\n\n> "We believe AI infrastructure in space can utilize the virtually limitless power of the Sun and thereby enable the use of AI as a transformative force for understanding the universe."\n\n> "We are rapidly constructing AI compute infrastructure — starting on Earth with the goal of extending to space."\n\nStarship is described as designed to "carry crew, cargo, satellites, and data centers to Earth orbit, the Moon, Mars, and beyond," which could conceptually link AI compute to space deployment, but no specific Starlink integration is mentioned.\n\n### 5. No Disclosed Inter-Segment Revenue or Cost Allocations Between AI and Connectivity\nThe MD&A sections detailing segment-level revenue and cost changes discuss each segment independently:\n\n- **Connectivity revenue drivers**: Starlink subscriber growth, enterprise adoption, network efficiency, MNO partnerships\n- **AI revenue drivers**: Advertising on X, Grok and X subscriptions, data licensing, API access\n- **Connectivity cost drivers**: Satellite depreciation, Starlink Kit costs, operating expenses\n- **AI cost drivers**: GPU hardware depreciation, cloud computing, data center infrastructure\n\nThere is no line item or narrative disclosure of revenue, cost, or infrastructure sharing between the AI and Connectivity segments.\n\n### 6. Elimination of Historical Related-Party Transactions\nThe document notes that the xAI/X Mergers were accounted for as common-control reorganizations, and that "all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation." This refers to pre-merger transactions between xAI and X, not to any AI-Connectivity relationship.\n\n## Summary\n\n| Question | Answer from the Document |\n|----------|------------------------|\n| Are there disclosed data flows between X/Grok and Starlink? | **No** |\n| Is there content distribution via Starlink for X/Grok? | **No** |\n| Is there shared infrastructure between the two segments? | **No** (AI uses terrestrial data centers like COLOSSUS; Starlink uses LEO satellites) |\n| Is there any indirect linkage? | Yes — both depend on the **Space segment** for launch capacity, and the company expresses a **vision** of eventually extending AI compute to space |\n| Is X\'s data role connected to Starlink? | No — X is described as a data engine for the **AI ecosystem (Grok)**, not for Connectivity |\n\nThe document presents the AI and Connectivity segments as parallel pillars of a vertically integrated company, with the Space segment serving as the foundational enabler for both, but with no disclosed direct operational integration between Starlink and X/Grok.',
